04114nam a22006735i 9781442679573DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20192000onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426795737 a10.3138/97814426795732doi  a(DE-B1597)496964  a(OCoLC)1083624486  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aE99.E7bD334 1999eb 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a306/.089/971209821 aDahl, Jens, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSaqqaq :bAn Inuit Hunting Community in the Modern World /cJens Dahl. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMaps -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Community, Its People and History -- t2. A Communal Complex: Hunting Beluga -- t3. Strategic Fishing, or Fishing by Choice -- t4. Ecology of Staple Food: Sealing -- t5. Man and Territory -- t6. Cooperation, Exchange, and Division of Labour -- t7. An Inuit Hunting Mode of Production -- t8. National Policy - Local Setting -- t9. Community and Nation -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the early eighteenth century, West Greenland became a colonial territory of Denmark. Nevertheless, a large number of Inuit communities maintained significant aspects of their cultural and economic practices. When home rule was introduced in 1979, the benign paternalism of colonial days was superseded by the incorporation of ethnic and institutional relations under a unified political system in Greenland. A national Greenlandic Inuit community was created, forcing further cultural adaptation on the part of the Inuit.Jens Dahl analyses life in Saqqaq, a small Greenlandic hunting community, and explores the changes that have taken place there over the last couple of decades. As modern technology is introduced and the worldviews of the Greenlandic Inuit change, the hunting community continues to base its life on a traditional notions, including an economy involving sharing, exchanging, and free access to the hunting and fishing grounds. Dahl demonstrates that Saqqaq and other communities have adapted to colonial and post-colonial influences by combining their practices of hunting and fishing with other forms of employment. In the midst of these economic developments, however, hunters are losing control over their traditional lands. Dahl discusses this conflict within the political context, making "Saqqaq" a unique and valuable example of Inuit survival in the modern world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aInuitxFishingzGreenlandzSaqqaq. 0aInuitxHuntingzGreenlandzSaqqaq. 0aInuitzGreenlandzSaqqaqxSocial life and customs. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144267957340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442679573423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442679573.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK